				<div class="postbody">
				Raviel, I can not believe you fell for that article you linked.  I read most of it, but what I did conclude ist that the guy wrote a huge amount of techno-babble @#%$.
<br />
He was, typical of somebody who does not know what they are talking about, just threw out a bunch of 'big' words to try to sound impressive.
<br />

<br />
First clue that the guy has no idea what he is talking about lies amongst the first paragraphs when he mentiones linear progress as opposed to exponential progress.
<br />
Okay, the problem is his entire arguement comes from the stand that people do believe in a linear progress.  People, though, do not believe in linear progression, we naturally believe in what he calls exponential progression.  In fact I think the typical Joe Blow consumer demands exponential advances in technology; people want computers twice as fast, memory twice as large, resolution twice as good.
<br />

<br />
My point, though, is that when the author makes the assumption about what society believes and that entire assumption is wrong, the rest of his conclusions, therefore, are wrong.
<br />
If you can not get the first step of a theory correct, then every following conclusion must incorrect.
<br />

<br />
He also assumes that Moore's Law is an actual scientific law; it is not.  It was just some guy making a very powerful statement that just happens to have been somewhat true.  There is not a signle shred of scientific evidence to support Moore's Law.
<br />
It is a very good guess that has worked out thus far.
<br />

<br />
The problem with this Kurzweil guy is that he tries to argue 'scientifically' against Moore's Law.  Again it is similar to what I mentioned earlier, if he can not even get the groundwork right his conclusions are nullified.
<br />

<br />
As it stands now, we do not even fully understand how memories are actually stored in the brain.  Sure, there are some good ideas on some matters; however, again we have no clue understanding of exactly how the brain works.
<br />

<br />
We need to understand how the brain works before we dare try to download it to a computer.
<br />

<br />
The first post in reponse to the guys article is a pretty good summary of what I think; and, more importantly, what the truth behind it is.
<br />

<br />
The author makes up calculations, makes up facts to support his opinion and yet manages to fail in mentioning a single concrete scientific source.
<br />

<br />
The guy may know a thing or two about computer technology, but is rather clueless in the fields of real science; physics, biology, chemistry.
<br />
He would be the guy I would lock in the back room to invent me a new computer monitor, not somebody  giving his opinions about the evolution of society.<br />
