			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				The linked article uses facts to back up everything it references, and was written by a man with 11 PhDs, two bestselling science books, and 9 successful multimillion dollar business ventures who is considered to be the number one scientist of all time in the field of artificial intelligence. His mantle is crowded with technical awards of nobel-prize caliber. I'm a bit reluctant to label someone with those qualifications a crackpot. Especially when what he's saying is so bloody obvious in the first place. Feel free to refute his credentials if you want, but I'm not that arrogant. 
<br />

<br />
As for Moore's law, it'll last about ten seconds past the first multi-layer processor - that is, a processor that is built inside a 3D cube using 3D designs instead of a 2D grid. That'll happen right about the time when they get down to molecule-sized microprocessors as the standard, which IBM has already built and tested successfully. When that happens, Moore's law fails because your computing power is now going up by cubes instead of squares. Moore's law also rather ignores quantum computing, which throw some amazing curve balls into the mix because it does so many types of math almost instantly in ways classical computers couldn't duplicate without decades of calculation. The addition of a quantum-computing unit to conventional processors essentially breaks all computer paradigms. Moore's law is a <span style="font-style: italic">highly</span> conservative estimate of computing power, that was basically as you say, a lucky guess, and we are well past its relevance... but the difference is that we're going to exceed its predictions, not succumb to them.
<br />

<br />
Joe blow doesn't know the difference between a linear and exponential curve, and wouldn't recognize one if it kicked him down a flight of stairs. All he cares about is that tomorrows toys are faster / better / cheaper than today's toys. Fifty years ago we didn't have computers, and right now we'd be useless without them. Saying we won't ever decode the brain is like saying we'd never have color television. Of course we will, it's just a question of when, and how. We just decoded the entire human genome, something considered impossible 10 years ago. Heck, Monday was the first ever private space flight. Things are looking up.
<br />

<br />
The only thing I take issue with in the article is the timeline. I think he's off by a hundred years at least. He's overlooking the fact that the exponential growth is only affecting developed areas of the world, as least for the time being. There are a number of restraining factors he is not taking into account. His conclusions still seems very sound.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
