			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Rav, i havn't had a good chance to sit down and read the whole thing. However, so far I'm inclined to agree with Xianin. The guy tries to say that technological evolution is a natural extension of biological evolution. 
<br />

<br />
Taking that standpoint, you could say that with a runaway positive feedback loop (human brain evolution, Evolutionary Arms races, ect) you would have an exponential growth of a particular trait. However, there are physical limitations to how far any particular trait can advance. 
<br />

<br />
For example, human brain size. Human brain size increased rapidly between generations. Cause? Unknown although there are a few very good theories to date. Why did the average population brain size stop growing between generations? Because the birth path between the pelvis was too small to accommodate a larger brain.
<br />

<br />
For example, cheetah running speed. Cheetahs are fast animals; they gained their speed rapidly over the course of a few years (relatively speaking). However, we have not seen a speed increase in cheetahs in a few hundred thousand years. Why? The physics to increase the speed of a cheetah would have too high of an energy cost is probably not worth it.
<br />

<br />
Instead of these particular traits advancing further at a huge cost relative to the gains, you might have another trait advance such as camouflage so that the cheetah would not have to run quite as fast.
<br />

<br />
The point I am trying to hit on here, involves the physical limitations of technology. We may be on the exponential growth portion of the technology evolution graph~ however, tomorrow we might hit a ceiling of advancement. We could branch out, and improve our other processes, but whatever portions of technology that hit the ceiling will be at a standstill, where improving the design will not give a significant improvement compared to the cost. In a capitalistic society, cost is everything.
<br />

<br />
I also like how this guy references average life expectancy. However, what he does not include is that the life expectancy of a human is no longer improving. We have reached the human limitation of life expectancy, and once again, any improvement to technology to try to increase the life expectancy would be too costly to show such a small gain. Instead, we should focus on technology that improves the quality of life during those years. 
<br />

<br />
I need to finish reading this and I will probably comment later, if and when I have time.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
