			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I just thought of some other stuff that I am going to throw out in the open.
<br />

<br />
First, something I have noticed in both 'real life' and moreso on the internet is that computer technology type people understand so very little about, what I like to call, the real sciences; biology, chemistry, geology, physics, etc.  On the other hand most scientists have no problem using and developing technology.
<br />

<br />
I think Kurzweil is a perfect, if extreme, example.  I do not disparage or othewise wish to nullify any of his achievements in the field of computer related technology.  However, at least in that article, has very little understanding of biological evolution.  He does, though, do a good job of throwing out some anatomy words to sounds impressive.  However, I can upen up my Biology 101 textbook from college and throw out a bunch of cool sounding words too.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The brain is not one huge "tabula rasa" (i.e., undifferentiated blank slate), but rather an intricate and intertwined collection of hundreds of specialized regions.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Whoa, deep.  So, our brains have different regions?  Wow, glad he cleared that up for us.
<br />

<br />
Stylx made a few good points, which in a way scares me.
<br />
Biological evolution and technical evolution are two entirely different beasts.
<br />

<br />
I fall into a crowd of people who believe that human technology has essentially nullified any sort of biological evolution that has taken place.  Biological evolution is going to, essentialy, cease to be as there is an increase in technology.
<br />
I gotta figure out if there is a term for people that think like that.
<br />

<br />
Anyhow, due to technology we have instances were people are basically living when they should be dying and giving birth when they should be sterile.
<br />
It is kind of harsh to say, but the fact is if people are not able to breed then they probably should not be breeding.  If a person is medically unable to live past the age of two, then evolutionary speaking, they should not be living.
<br />
However, again, technology has made it so that these people are living and spreading their genetic material into society.  We are basically contaminating our own DNA; man, I sound like Hitler now.
<br />

<br />
We as a species have no major need or reason to develop some leap in evolution.  
<br />

<br />
In order to understand my point, I am going to backtrack and mention something about biological evolution.
<br />
Evolution is easily misunderstood by most and I think not because it is too complicated, but because it is simple; parsimonious is the word that scientists love to throw around.
<br />
Evolution ulitimately would lead to an incrase in fitness.  Fitness is not really defined as being stronger, faster, and smarter, but rather the ability to have more viable offspring.  If you are faster and stronger than I am, it does you no good if you can not breed.
<br />
In most cases, though, the faster and stronger animal does have more viable offspring.  
<br />
<a href="http://users.rcn.com/jkimball.ma.ultranet/BiologyPages/E/Evolution.html#Fitness" target="_blank" class="postlink">HERE</a> is something I googled up that may make sense.  I didn't read all of it, but the fitness portion is what I did read.
<br />

<br />
So, biological evolution is basically a chance mutation that increases fitness and therefore gets passed on into the population.
<br />

<br />
Getting back to my point about technology and evolution, the chance of a human evolutionary change actually affecting our species is about null.  Not completely true, however technology nullifies any positive impact that a change could have.
<br />

<br />
For example maybe somebody develops a mutation that makes them more heat tolerant.  Okay, that is cool for them, but in the age of sunscreen, indoor air conditioning and medical prevention the positive impact of that mutation is basically meaningless.
<br />

<br />
I would like to see some more studies about reverse engineering the brain, as Kurzweil mentions.  However, I think in a typicial computer-type person way, he fails to tkae notice that the brain is not some stand alone organ.  In the technology world you can increase HDD space, RAM, video and whatever else all as stand alone advnaces.  Sure everything eventually needs to take a leap forward, but I can buy a bigger HDD right now without upgrading my entire computer.
<br />
You can not, though, rebuild the brain via reverse engineering in the same fashion.  Simple and easy explanation is the hormone regulation that happens in the body.  Stuff enters and leaves the brain (so to speak) so the brain is not neccesarily isolated.
<br />

<br />
I think the guy does have some ideas for a killer sci-fi series.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
